<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>The three miners' families are expected to congregate in Barberton in remembrance of the three miners.Nkambule, Nyarenda and Mnisi were in a lamp room housed in a shipping container on the surface of the coal mine, when an underground supporting pillar collapsed on 5 February 2016.The container was buried under about 60m of rock and soil, and seventy miners were rescued using a ventilation shaft.Rescuers tried time after time to get to the three, trapped underground, but had to withdraw as more ground collapsed.The families of the three trapped Lily mineworkers were each paid a lump sum of R200 000, while Seventy five of the injured miners were paid R10 000, as compared to the original amount promised of R50 000.Meanwhile, Mineral Resources Minister Mosebenzi Zwane says the inquiry into the Lily Mine tragedy has been completed and a report will be submitted to the Department of Mineral Resources next week.